\end{center}

\section{Falsifiability}

Three independent falsifiability conditions:
\begin{description}[leftmargin=2em]
\item[F1.] Absence of spiral enrichment ($x_0' = x_0$, no accumulated $z$) in
  $\mathrm{dm}^3$ contact simulations above the $g^{33}$ stability index would
  refute~T1.
\item[F2.] Violation of $\mathrm{dm}^3$ structural stability ($\varepsilon_0 = 1/3$)
  under operator perturbations within the stated bounds would refute~T1.
\item[F3.] A formal proof in Lean~4 (AXLE repository) that the Gronwall bound does
  not imply transverse contraction toward $\Gamma$ would refute~T1.
\end{description}

\section{Research Directions}

The contact-geometric results of Sections~5--6 are classical dissipative dynamics.
The connections described below are structural analogies and open research problems,
not theorems. No retrocausal claims are made in this paper.

\subsection{Operator Grammar and Time-Symmetric Quantum Mechanics}

The two-state vector formalism (TSVF) of Aharonov and Vaidman~\cite{aharonov2001}
assigns both a forward-evolving and a backward-evolving state to each quantum system.
The operator chain $G = U \circ F \circ K \circ C$ has a structural resemblance to
this bidirectional picture: the Fold operator $F$ introduces self-reference at
mid-circuit, and the Unfold operator $U$ projects outward. Whether this resemblance
can be made precise is an open problem. No retrocausal claim is made in this paper.

\textbf{Open Problem 8.1.} Construct, if possible, a functor from the $\mathrm{dm}^3$
operator category to the category of pre- and post-selected quantum states in the
TSVF, preserving the stability radius $\varepsilon_0 = 1/3$.

\subsection{Delayed-Choice Experiments and the Fold Operator}

In the delayed-choice quantum eraser (Kim et al.~\cite{kim2000}), a future
measurement choice determines which past path information is available. The Fold
operator $F$ is structurally analogous to the beam-splitter choice in that experiment.
This analogy motivates the following research direction but does not constitute a
proof of any physical connection.

\textbf{Open Problem 8.2.} Identify an experimental observable in a quantum optics or
NMR system that would distinguish spiral enrichment ($x_0' \neq x_0$ after circuit
closure) from linear return ($x_0' = x_0$), and determine whether the $\mathrm{dm}^3$
stability index $g^{33}$ has a measurable counterpart in that system.

\subsection{Entanglement Swapping and the Spiral Return}

Ma et al.~\cite{ma2012} demonstrated entanglement swapping between photons that never
coexisted. The spiral return $x_0 \to x_{64} \to x_0'$ with $x_0' \neq x_0$ is
formally analogous: the source state is enriched without returning to its original
configuration. Whether this formal analogy corresponds to a physical mechanism is
unknown.

\textbf{Open Problem 8.3.} Determine whether the contact-geometric spiral return,
formalized via the Floquet multiplier $\lambda_\perp = \exp(-4\pi)$, admits a quantum
information interpretation consistent with the entanglement swapping results of
Ma et al.~\cite{ma2012}.

\subsection{Negative Group Delay and the Weave Scale}

Angulo et al.~\cite{angulo2024} report experimental evidence of negative group delay
--- a well-understood phenomenon in classical wave optics (anomalous dispersion) that
does not require retrocausality. The $\mathrm{dm}^3$ framework does not explain or
predict negative group delay. The reference is included as research context only.

\subsection{Formal Verification in AXLE (Lean 4)}

The AXLE repository (\texttt{github.com/TOTOGT/AXLE}) contains Lean~4 proof
obligations for the $\mathrm{dm}^3$ framework. The highest-priority open items are:
\begin{enumerate}[label=(\alph*), leftmargin=*]
\item Formal verification of the Gronwall bound and $\varepsilon_0 = 1/3$
  (Section~6) --- currently the most tractable target.
\item Formalization of the $g$-series taxonomy (Definition~2.2) as a Lean~4
  inductive type, with the index-33 conjecture stated as a \texttt{sorry} to be
  discharged by future work.
\item The Poincar\'{e}-to-Collatz correspondence --- the hardest open item,
  currently marked as a \texttt{sorry} in AXLE --- is not required for the results
  of this paper.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Contemporaneous Convergence: Navr\'{a}til (2026)}

Navr\'{a}til~\cite{navratil2026} independently constructs a geometric Hilbert space
with inner product $\langle j|k\rangle = \eta^{-k}\delta_{jk}$ and geometric Born
rule $P_G(k) = |c_k|^2\eta^{-k}$, departing from the $\mathrm{SL}(3,\mathbb{Z})$
Tribonacci algebra and a discrete integer lattice rather than a contact manifold.
The Tribonacci constant $\eta \approx 1.839$ (the dominant root of
$\eta^3 - \eta^2 - \eta - 1 = 0$) appears in both frameworks as a natural structural
weight, though the derivation paths are independent. This convergence on $\eta^{-k}$
is noted as an open structural question: whether the $\mathrm{dm}^3$ contact geometry
and the $\mathrm{SL}(3,\mathbb{Z})$ algebraic lattice are dual descriptions of the
same underlying structure remains to be determined.

\textbf{Open Problem 8.6.} Determine whether there exists a natural transformation or
adjunction between the $\mathrm{dm}^3$ contact-geometric framework (this paper,
Volumes~I--II) and the $\mathrm{SL}(3,\mathbb{Z})$ Tribonacci algebra of
Navr\'{a}til~\cite{navratil2026} that maps $\varepsilon_0 = 1/3$ to a corresponding
structural constant in the algebraic lattice setting.

